vim.api.nvim_set_keymap('n', 'gf', '<cmd>lua vim.lsp.buf.formatting()<cr>', {noremap = true})
```

nvim edit the following file

```c
int main(void) {
  float a =  log(0);
  bbbbbbbbbbbb(log(0));
  float ccccccccccc = 1;
}
```

as follows

![bug](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/514522/107162369-742e3f00-699a-11eb-84a7-1bd516569ab9.gif)

I type `gf` to format the file and cause the error.

Given a file in this state (I have the go treesitter parser installed from the grammar, and a gopls based lsp setup)
```
package main

import (

)

type test struct {
	a string
}

func main() {
	fmt.Println("Hello World")
}

func newTest() *test {
	return &test{
		a: "test",
	}
}
```
With `noexpandtab` if I go to column 0 of line 4, enter insert mode and insert a tab `i<tab>`, I see a `end_col value outside range` error on line 18.

With `expandtab` I do not get that error.

With #14124 rebased on master (because of the tree-sitter ABI change) and `noexpandtab` I do not get that error.

I do however continue to see that error in my real development flows but I am unable to create a minimal reproduction. In those cases, I cannot reproduce if I disable my `gopls` based language server. In those cases, I usually see the error by adding an extra tab to an empty line, exiting insert mode, and deleting the line. For example if I have

```
func f() {
<tab>fmt.Println("hello world")
}
```
and I modify this to
```
func f() {
<tab><tab>
<tab>fmt.Println("hello world")
}
```

and then delete the line with two tabs, I see the error.

I also experience similar problem. 
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/14362650/117194845-4156e400-aded-11eb-9203-88b53e5ff066.png)

